{
    "analysis": "We examined the top 20 anomalous (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pairs in the incident window and attempted to identify fault runs using a strict filter (run_length >= 2 AND breach_percent > 0.5). No runs passed that filter, so no high-confidence metric-level faults were found. This leaves two paths: (1) relax the fault-filter criteria to surface borderline sustained anomalies that might indicate the root cause, and (2) use trace and log analysis to find downstream impact or corroborating evidence. Per the workflow, we should first surface any borderline metric runs (longer runs or moderate breaches) so we can prioritize components for trace/log inspection.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Inspect the previously stored df_detected_runs (runs detected before strict filtering) and produce a compact candidate list using more permissive criteria: keep runs where either (run_length >= 2) OR (breach_percent >= 0.2). For these candidate runs produce up to top 20 rows ordered by breach_percent descending. Each row must include: cmdb_id, kpi_name, breach_type, start_timestamp, end_timestamp, run_length, extremal_value, p95, p5, breach_percent. Also return a small aggregate: counts of candidate runs per cmdb_id (top 10). Store the filtered candidates in kernel variable df_candidate_faults for the next step." }

{
    "analysis": "We expanded metric-level analysis to a permissive candidate set and found a small number of borderline runs: MG02 (OSLinux-CPU_CPULoad) has a 2-point above-P95 run with ~22.6% breach; IG01 shows a single-point large below-P5 JVM heap drop (~32%); MG01 has several low-severity CPU related runs. No high-confidence metric fault (>=2 points AND >50% breach) was found. According to the workflow, with multiple candidate faulty components at the same level we should use traces next to localize the root cause (identify downstream faulty service or corroborating latency spikes). Logs should be inspected in parallel if traces are inconclusive, but earlier summaries showed log entries concentrated on Tomcat/Mysql and error_logs is empty. Therefore the next step is trace analysis focused on the candidate components (MG02, MG01, IG01) and their traces inside the incident window to see whether there are significant trace anomalies (e.g., latency p95/mean spikes) that align with the candidate metric runs' earliest timestamps.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using kernel variables df_trace and the incident window computed before, do the following:\n1) Restrict df_trace to rows where cmdb_id is one of ['MG01','MG02','IG01'] and compute global P95 and P5 for each (cmdb_id, trace_name) pair using the full available series. Save as df_trace_thresholds with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, p95, p5, total_points.\n2) Filter df_trace to the incident window (Mar 23, 2021 16:30–17:00 UTC+8) and for each (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute: total_points_in_window, count_above_p95 (value > p95), count_below_p5 (value < p5), earliest_timestamp_above_p95, earliest_timestamp_below_p5.\n3) Return a compact result limited to top 20 rows ordered by max(count_above_p95, count_below_p5) descending. For each row include: cmdb_id, trace_name, p95, p5, total_points_in_window, count_above_p95, count_below_p5, earliest_timestamp_above_p95, earliest_timestamp_below_p5.\nAlso return the total number of (cmdb_id,trace_name) pairs evaluated. Store intermediate tables df_trace_thresholds and df_trace_incident in the kernel for follow-up steps."
}

